Where is this stated in the spec, that MessageId should be 2 digits?

The 2nd paragraph of this commit message goes through the exact section and quote from the spec, so I'm a little confused at this question.  Is there something else you were looking for aside from the section number and quote from the spec?
Duh, too much turkey last week. ;)
Gotta love Turkey.  Next year go for Brisket.
I guess you meant 2 here?
yep.

I think it is a breaking change in practice too. Here https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/webui-vue/+/72589/6#message-8e00433c508f7b2eed0b95116c438fd2d0235218 I noticed the inconsistency and asked if the standard had a typo. Getting no reply I assumed yes, and followed with what was implemented in bmcweb at the time. So until the last revision of https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/webui-vue/+/74371 (thank you Jason for taking care of this detail promptly) is merged webui-vue would remain broken I'm afraid.

https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/webui-vue/+/74371

Looks like it was meant to handle either 2 or 3 digit, but that's a fair point, this could break folks.

Do you think it's worth having an opt-out option?

> https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/webui-vue/+/74371
> 
> Looks like it was meant to handle either 2 or 3 digit, but that's a fair point, this could break folks.

Only the latest version pushed few days ago can handle both, the one before it couldn't.

> Do you think it's worth having an opt-out option?

In my opinion no, it would increase complexity unjustifiably. Please just merge that 74371 to webui-vue first.
I put in an option if only for documentation of the change and when it would be removed.  The actual code added is one more branch and one extra std::format statement.
Done
Low risk of breaking, test if you can. If not, I am okay with this.
I'll at least run this through service validator.  Just wanted to make sure everyone was ok with not having the back path first.
service validator sounds great. Myung also tested HeartbeatEvent messageId
It looks good to me
@Myung does this solve the problem you had on the other patch?

Yes, it works good as HeartbeatEvent messageId conforms the spec like
```
  "Events": [
    {
      "@odata.type": "#Message.v1_1_1.Message",
...
      "Message": "Redfish service is functional.",
      "MessageArgs": [],
      "MessageId": "HeartbeatEvent.1.0.RedfishServiceFunctional", <===
      "MessageSeverity": "OK",
      "OriginOfCondition": "/redfish/v1/EventService/Subscriptions/1023288406",
      "Resolution": "None."
    }
  ],
 ```
Thank you for testing.
Adding Paul as we had discussed this issue in the past on webui-vue

can these 3 members be unsigned int?

Or is there a need for negative version numbers.

Considering that the versions strings are optional, I made these -1 for the case where a registry might not use a 3 digit version string, so we could set them to -1 in that case.

There isn't a DMTF registry that follows that yet, so if we really want these as uint and change them when such time comes, I can make that change.
Changed.

nit: since the version is already defined by the 3 integers, 
is 'char* registryVersion' still needed?
Probably not.  It's been removed in the latest patch.  Thanks for the idea.
This patchset seems even better than the previous patchset.
